{
  "masechta": "Zevachim",
  "daf": 70,
  "amud": "a",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction to the Debate: Melikah of a Treifah Bird and Tumah Status",
      "display_title": "Melikah Treifah Bird",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening: Three-way debate on whether melikah of a treifah bird causes tumah",
          "display_title": "Opening",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Meir vs. Rabbi Yehuda: Different standards for birds vs. behemot regarding treifah status",
          "display_title": "Meir vs. Yehuda",
          "timestamp": "00:55"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's source: Reading the word treifah literally from the pasuk about eating neveilah and treifah",
          "display_title": "Yehuda's Source",
          "timestamp": "01:50"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Gemara's Challenge: Can treifah be read literally or does it teach something else?",
      "display_title": "Treifah Interpretation",
      "timestamp": "02:10",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Gemara questions whether treifah in the pasuk is literal or teaches that we only discuss kosher animals",
          "display_title": "Literal vs. Exclusion",
          "timestamp": "02:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Example from Devarim: cholev neveilah and cholev treifah—does treifah imply the meat is tamei for a treifah (unlike neveilah)?",
          "display_title": "Cholev Example",
          "timestamp": "02:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's resolution: The word treifah excludes non-kosher animals (mi sheyesh bemino treifah), not implying treifah meat is tamei",
          "display_title": "Mi Sheyesh Bemino",
          "timestamp": "03:41"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Question of Cholev Status in Different Animals and the Role of Treifah",
      "display_title": "Cholev Tahor Issue",
      "timestamp": "04:05",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Abaye: Treifah is literal but serves to exclude the comparison to non-kosher animals; treifah meat is tahor unlike neveilah",
          "display_title": "Abaye's Position",
          "timestamp": "04:05"
        },
        {
          "title": "Why treifah is necessary: To prevent thinking treifah is like non-kosher animals (tamei) and thus has tamei cholev",
          "display_title": "Treifah vs. Tameia",
          "timestamp": "10:20"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's approach: Treifah is literal to teach that both issurim (neveilah and treifah) apply to the cholev",
          "display_title": "Rava's Approach",
          "timestamp": "15:57"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Derashah on Cholev Neveilah and Treifah: Determining if the pasuk speaks of kosher or non-kosher animals",
      "display_title": "Cholev Derashah",
      "timestamp": "29:38",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Braita: How do we know cholev is tahor only for kosher animals? Comparison of neveilah and shechitah status",
          "display_title": "Neveilah Shechitah",
          "timestamp": "29:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Alternative path: The bird case where non-kosher animals are tahor for neveilah; should cholev apply to non-kosher?",
          "display_title": "Bird Exception",
          "timestamp": "32:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Resolution: The word treifah teaches we are only discussing kosher animals (mi sheyesh bemino treifah)",
          "display_title": "Treifah Resolution",
          "timestamp": "35:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Braita continues: The word 'achol' (eating) teaches we only discuss animals whose cholev is forbidden, excluding chayah",
          "display_title": "Achol Teaching",
          "timestamp": "39:12"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Case of Non-Kosher Birds: Clarifying the Braita's Surprising Statement",
      "display_title": "Non-Kosher Birds",
      "timestamp": "41:19",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Yaakov bar Abba challenges Rava: How can a neveilah of a non-kosher animal be tahor?",
          "display_title": "Rav Yaakov Challenge",
          "timestamp": "41:19"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's clarification: The braita refers to the bird world where non-kosher birds' neveilah is tahor",
          "display_title": "Rava Clarification",
          "timestamp": "41:49"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Limits of Rabbi Meir's Position: How far does the principle extend regarding blemished birds?",
      "display_title": "Rabbi Meir Limits",
      "timestamp": "43:02",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yochanan: Rabbi Meir's position only applies to temimim (unblemished birds), not ba'alei mumin (blemished birds)",
          "display_title": "Temimim Only",
          "timestamp": "43:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Elazar: Rabbi Meir applies even to ba'alei mumin; once treifah is not neveilah, neither is a blemished bird",
          "display_title": "Even Ba'alei Mumin",
          "timestamp": "43:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Bibi quoting Rabbi Elazar: Rabbi Meir permits melikah on ducks and chickens without becoming neveilah",
          "display_title": "Chickens Ducks",
          "timestamp": "44:15"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Question of Eglah Arufah: Does breaking the neck make it tahor like melikah?",
      "display_title": "Eglah Arufah",
      "timestamp": "45:39",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Yirmiah's question: If melikah of sanctified treifah bird is not neveilah, what about using a goat for eglah arufah?",
          "display_title": "Rav Yirmiah",
          "timestamp": "45:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Hidden assumption uncovered: Is eglah arufah itself tahor (not neveilah)?",
          "display_title": "Eglah Arufah Status",
          "timestamp": "49:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "House of Rabbi Yannai: Eglah arufah is treated as pseudo-korban (kaparah) comparable to kodashim",
          "display_title": "Pseudo-Korban",
          "timestamp": "50:11"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Braita on Eglah Arufah Cholev: Determining when the meat is tamei and when cholev is tahor",
      "display_title": "Eglah Arufah Cholev",
      "timestamp": "51:29",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Braita source: Cholev of shor haniskal and eglah arufah (which are neveilah) are still tahor via 'kol chelev'",
          "display_title": "Kol Chelev",
          "timestamp": "51:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "The problem: If cholev is tahor, does that imply meat is tamei for eglah arufah?",
          "display_title": "Implication",
          "timestamp": "52:47"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's solution: When merikah (breaking neck) is performed correctly, entire eglah arufah is tahor; pasuk teaches case where animal dies before breaking neck",
          "display_title": "Merikah Solution",
          "timestamp": "53:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "The moment of prohibition: Bringing eglah arufah down to the nachal eitan gives it status and forbids benefit before merikah",
          "display_title": "Yeridato L'Nachal",
          "timestamp": "54:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Unresolved: What if a goat (instead of calf) is used for eglah arufah—is it tahor according to Rabbi Meir?",
          "display_title": "Goat Unresolved",
          "timestamp": "56:18"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
